<p><b>Shiva</b> (pronunciation: <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ʃɪ.ʋə]</span>; <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: शिव, <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Śiva</span></i>, lit. "Auspicious one" ) is a major <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hindu</a> god and one aspect of <a href="/wiki/Trimurti" title="Trimurti">Trimurti</a>. In the <a href="/wiki/Shaiva" title="Shaiva" class="mw-redirect">Shaiva</a> tradition of Hinduism, Shiva is seen as the supreme God. In the <a href="/wiki/Smarta" title="Smarta" class="mw-redirect">Smarta</a> tradition, he is one of <a href="/wiki/Panchadeva" title="Panchadeva" class="mw-redirect">the five primary forms of God</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Flood_1996.2C_p._17_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Flood_1996.2C_p._17-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Followers of Hinduism who focus their worship upon Shiva are called Shaivites or Shaivas (Sanskrit <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Śaiva</span>).<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> Shaivism, along with <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Vaiṣṇava</span> traditions that focus on <a href="/wiki/Vishnu" title="Vishnu">Vishnu</a> and <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Śākta</span> traditions that focus on the <a href="/wiki/Devi" title="Devi">goddess</a> <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn"><a href="/wiki/Dev%C4%AB" title="Devī" class="mw-redirect">Devī</a></span> are three of the most influential denominations in Hinduism.<sup id="cite_ref-Flood_1996.2C_p._17_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Flood_1996.2C_p._17-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Shiva is usually worshipped in the form of <i><a href="/wiki/Lingam" title="Lingam">Shiva linga</a></i>. In images, he is generally represented as immersed in deep meditation or dancing the <i><a href="/wiki/Tandava" title="Tandava">Tandava</a></i> upon <a href="/wiki/Mayasura" title="Mayasura">Maya</a>, the demon of ignorance in his manifestation of <a href="/wiki/Nataraja" title="Nataraja">Nataraja</a>, the lord of the dance.</p>
<p>In some other Hindu denominations, <a href="/wiki/Brahma" title="Brahma">Brahma</a>, Vishnu, and Shiva represent the three primary aspects of the divine in Hinduism and are collectively known as the Trimurti. In this school of religious thought, Brahma is the creator, Vishnu is the maintainer or preserver, and Shiva is the destroyer or transformer.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
